{"id":"seed:en:sun","source":"seed:en:sun","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"The Sun is the star at the centre of our solar system. It is a giant ball of very hot gas, mostly hydrogen and helium, held together by its own gravity. Deep inside the Sun, the pressure is so great and the temperature so high — about 15 million degrees Celsius — that hydrogen atoms squash together to make helium. This process is called nuclear fusion, and it releases enormous amounts of energy. The energy travels outward through the Sun for hundreds of thousands of years before reaching the surface, and from there it shines into space as light and heat.\n\nThe Sun is much bigger than the Earth. About 1.3 million Earths could fit inside it. Even though it looks small in the sky, the Sun is so far away — about 150 million kilometres — that its light takes around eight minutes to reach us. When you look at the sunset, you are seeing light that left the Sun eight minutes earlier.\n\nThe Sun is the reason life on Earth is possible. Plants use sunlight to make their food in a process called photosynthesis. Animals (including us) eat the plants, or eat other animals that ate plants, so almost every living thing on Earth depends on the Sun's energy. The Sun also drives the weather: it heats the air and the oceans, which makes wind, clouds, and rain.\n\nLike all stars, the Sun has a life cycle. It formed about 4.6 billion years ago from a cloud of gas and dust, and it has enough hydrogen left to keep shining for about another 5 billion years. Eventually it will swell up into a kind of star called a red giant, then shed its outer layers and become a small, dense remnant called a white dwarf. That is a long time away — far longer than humans have existed.","topics":["space","sun","stars","fusion","solar system"]}
{"id":"seed:en:moon","source":"seed:en:moon","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"The Moon is Earth's only natural satellite — a round, rocky world that orbits Earth once every 27 days or so. It is about a quarter of Earth's diameter, which makes it unusually large compared to its planet. The Moon has no air to breathe and almost no water on its surface, so the sky there is always black, even during the day, and the ground is covered in fine grey dust and craters left by ancient impacts.\n\nThe Moon does not make its own light. What we see when the Moon shines is sunlight bouncing off its surface. Because the Moon orbits Earth and Earth orbits the Sun, the part of the Moon that we can see lit up changes over the month. This is why the Moon goes through phases: a thin crescent grows into a half, then a fuller shape, then a full Moon, and then shrinks back the other way. A full cycle of phases takes about 29.5 days.\n\nThe Moon always shows us the same face. This is because it spins on its own axis at exactly the same rate that it orbits Earth — a coincidence that is actually caused by Earth's gravity slowly tugging on the Moon over billions of years. The far side of the Moon was a complete mystery to humans until spacecraft photographed it in 1959.\n\nThe Moon's gravity also pulls on Earth's oceans, which is the main reason we have tides. Twice each day in most places, the sea level rises and falls because the water is being tugged toward the Moon.\n\nMost scientists think the Moon formed about 4.5 billion years ago when a Mars-sized object crashed into the young Earth. The debris from that collision came together in orbit and slowly clumped into the Moon we know today. Twelve people have walked on the Moon, all between 1969 and 1972, during the Apollo missions.","topics":["space","moon","tides","phases","apollo"]}
{"id":"seed:en:earth-orbit-day-night","source":"seed:en:earth-orbit-day-night","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Day and night happen because the Earth spins. Earth turns all the way around its own axis once every 24 hours, like a slowly spinning top. The half of the Earth that is facing the Sun is having day; the half facing away is having night. As the planet keeps turning, the day side rolls into night, and the night side rolls into day. This is why the Sun seems to rise in the east and set in the west — it is really the ground beneath your feet that is moving, not the Sun.\n\nAt the same time as it spins, Earth is also travelling around the Sun. One full trip around the Sun takes one year, or about 365.25 days. The extra quarter day is why we add an extra day to February every four years (a leap year).\n\nEarth's spinning axis is not straight up and down compared to its orbit; it is tilted by about 23.5 degrees. This tilt is what gives us seasons. When the part of Earth where you live is tilted toward the Sun, the Sun appears higher in the sky and the days are longer and warmer — that is summer. Six months later, your part of Earth is tilted away from the Sun, the Sun is lower, the days are shorter, and it is colder — that is winter. Spring and autumn are the in-between times.\n\nThe Northern Hemisphere and the Southern Hemisphere have opposite seasons because when one is tilted toward the Sun, the other is tilted away. So when it is summer in Australia, it is winter in Canada.\n\nEarth's spinning is what gives wind storms their swirl, what makes a free-falling object curve sideways slightly, and what stops the planet's atmosphere from settling on one side. Without the spin, one half of Earth would be permanently scorching and the other permanently frozen.","topics":["space","earth","day","night","seasons"]}
{"id":"seed:en:planets-solar-system","source":"seed:en:planets-solar-system","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Our solar system has eight planets that orbit the Sun. In order from nearest to farthest, they are Mercury, Venus, Earth, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune. The first four are called the rocky planets or terrestrial planets, because they have solid surfaces made mostly of rock and metal. The last four are the gas giants and ice giants — much bigger worlds made mostly of gas and liquid, with no solid surface to stand on.\n\nMercury is the smallest planet and the closest to the Sun. It has almost no atmosphere, which means its days are scorching and its nights are freezing. Venus is about the same size as Earth, but its thick clouds trap heat so well that it is actually the hottest planet — even hotter than Mercury, with a surface hot enough to melt lead.\n\nEarth is the only planet we know of with liquid water on its surface and life. Mars, the next planet out, is sometimes called the Red Planet because of the rusty iron in its dust. Mars has tall volcanoes, deep canyons, and signs that water once flowed there long ago.\n\nJupiter is by far the biggest planet — more than 300 times the mass of Earth. It has a famous storm called the Great Red Spot that has been swirling for at least 350 years. Saturn is famous for its bright rings, which are made of countless chunks of ice and rock orbiting the planet. All four giant planets have rings, but Saturn's are the brightest.\n\nUranus and Neptune are far out at the edge of the solar system, where the Sun is just a very bright star. They are extremely cold and have winds faster than the worst storms on Earth. Uranus is unusual because it spins on its side.\n\nBeyond Neptune are dwarf planets like Pluto, plus countless smaller icy bodies in a region called the Kuiper Belt.","topics":["space","planets","solar system","mercury","venus","mars","jupiter","saturn","uranus","neptune"]}
{"id":"seed:en:stars","source":"seed:en:stars","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Stars are giant balls of glowing gas, mostly hydrogen and helium. They form when a cloud of gas and dust in space slowly collapses under its own gravity. As the cloud squeezes together, it gets hotter and hotter. When the centre becomes hot enough — millions of degrees — hydrogen atoms start fusing together to make helium, releasing huge amounts of energy. That energy is what makes a star shine.\n\nThe Sun is a star, and it is the closest one to us. It looks much bigger and brighter than other stars only because it is so much closer. The next nearest star, Proxima Centauri, is more than 250,000 times farther away than the Sun. Even at the speed of light, its light takes more than four years to reach Earth.\n\nStars come in different sizes and colours. Cool stars are red, warmer stars are yellow or white, and the hottest stars are blue. The Sun is a yellow-white star of medium size and middle age. Some stars are tiny — only the size of a city — but extremely dense and made of leftover material from a star that exploded. Others are so big that if you put one where the Sun is, it would swallow up Earth and even Jupiter.\n\nStars do not last forever. They live by burning hydrogen, and when they run out of fuel, they change. Smaller stars like the Sun puff up into red giants, then shed their outer layers and end up as quiet white dwarfs. Very massive stars die more dramatically, exploding as supernovas. The explosion scatters the heavier elements the star made — carbon, oxygen, iron — into space, where they can become part of new stars and planets. The atoms in your body were made inside stars that lived and died long before the Sun was born.\n\nWhen you look up at a clear night sky, every twinkling point of light (except the planets) is a distant sun.","topics":["space","stars","fusion","supernova","stellar evolution"]}
{"id":"seed:en:galaxies-milky-way","source":"seed:en:galaxies-milky-way","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"A galaxy is an enormous group of stars, gas, dust, and dark matter held together by gravity. A typical galaxy contains hundreds of billions of stars. Galaxies come in different shapes: some are flat spirals with curving arms, some are smooth oval blobs called ellipticals, and some are irregular and lumpy.\n\nOur Sun and all the stars you can see at night belong to a galaxy called the Milky Way. The Milky Way is a spiral galaxy, shaped a bit like a pinwheel with a bright bulge in the middle. From the inside, it looks to us like a faint band of milky light stretching across the night sky — which is how it got its name. The Sun is about two-thirds of the way out from the centre, on one of the spiral arms.\n\nThe Milky Way is huge. Light, which travels faster than anything else, takes about 100,000 years to cross from one side of it to the other. Even so, the Milky Way is just one of more than two trillion galaxies in the part of the universe we can see.\n\nGalaxies are not scattered evenly through space. They cluster together in groups, and the groups gather into bigger structures called superclusters. Between the galaxies are vast empty spaces called voids.\n\nMost galaxies, including ours, have a supermassive black hole at their centre. The one in the Milky Way is called Sagittarius A*. It is millions of times the mass of the Sun, but it sits very quietly compared to the noisy black holes in some other galaxies.\n\nGalaxies sometimes drift close enough that their gravity pulls them together. When two galaxies merge, the stars rarely actually collide because they are so far apart, but the shapes of the galaxies are stretched and reshaped over hundreds of millions of years. The Milky Way will eventually merge with our nearest large galactic neighbour, the Andromeda galaxy, in about four billion years.","topics":["space","galaxies","milky way","andromeda","universe"]}
{"id":"seed:en:black-holes","source":"seed:en:black-holes","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"A black hole is a region of space where gravity is so strong that nothing — not even light — can escape from it once it gets close enough. That is why it is called black: no light comes out, so we cannot see it directly.\n\nBlack holes form when a very massive star runs out of fuel and collapses. The outer layers of the star are blasted away in a giant explosion called a supernova, while the core gets crushed inward by gravity. If the core is heavy enough, nothing can stop the collapse. All that matter ends up squashed into an unimaginably tiny point, and around that point is a sphere called the event horizon. The event horizon is the point of no return: anything that crosses it can never come back.\n\nFor anything outside the event horizon, a black hole is just a very strong source of gravity. If the Sun were magically replaced by a black hole of the same mass (which would be only a few kilometres across), the planets would keep orbiting just like before, because the gravity at our distance would be unchanged. We would freeze without sunlight, but Earth would not be sucked in.\n\nThere are two main sizes. Stellar-mass black holes are a few times the mass of the Sun and are the leftovers of dead massive stars. Supermassive black holes are millions or even billions of times the mass of the Sun and sit at the centres of galaxies. Astronomers think most galaxies have one.\n\nWe cannot see a black hole itself, but we can see what happens around it. Gas falling toward a black hole heats up to millions of degrees and glows brightly in X-rays before it disappears. In 2019, scientists released the first picture ever taken of the dark shadow of a black hole, surrounded by a glowing ring of hot gas.\n\nDespite their fearsome reputation, black holes are not cosmic vacuum cleaners. They only pull in things that get very close. Most of the universe is far too distant ever to fall into one.","topics":["space","black holes","gravity","supernova","event horizon"]}
{"id":"seed:en:comets-meteors","source":"seed:en:comets-meteors","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Comets and meteors are both small icy or rocky bits of the solar system, but they are not the same thing.\n\nA comet is a small body, usually only a few kilometres across, made of ice, dust, and frozen gases. Most comets spend their time far out in the cold edges of the solar system, where they stay frozen and dark. Sometimes a comet's orbit brings it close to the Sun. As it warms up, the ice turns to gas and dust streams out behind it, forming the comet's bright tail. The tail can be millions of kilometres long, but it is so thin you could almost see straight through it. A comet's tail always points away from the Sun, because the solar wind blows it like the wind blows a flag.\n\nFamous comets include Halley's Comet, which returns close to Earth roughly every 76 years and has been seen and recorded by people for at least two thousand years.\n\nMeteoroids are smaller — usually pieces of rock or metal, often no bigger than a grain of sand. Many of them are crumbs left behind by comets. When a meteoroid enters Earth's atmosphere, it slams into the air at very high speed, gets extremely hot, and glows as a streak of light across the sky. That streak is called a meteor or, in everyday language, a shooting star. Despite the name, it is not a star at all.\n\nMost meteoroids burn up completely in the atmosphere. A few are big enough that part of them survives the trip down and lands on the ground. Once a piece reaches the ground, we call it a meteorite. Some meteorites are pieces of asteroids, some are pieces of the Moon or Mars, blasted off by an ancient impact.\n\nWhen Earth passes through the dusty trail left by an old comet, you get a meteor shower: dozens of shooting stars per hour, all seeming to come from the same part of the sky. Famous meteor showers include the Perseids in August and the Geminids in December.","topics":["space","comets","meteors","meteor shower","halley"]}
{"id":"seed:en:eclipses","source":"seed:en:eclipses","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"An eclipse happens when one object in space gets in the way of another and casts a shadow. From Earth, the two kinds we can see are solar eclipses and lunar eclipses.\n\nA solar eclipse happens when the Moon passes between the Sun and Earth, blocking out part or all of the Sun's light for a short time. During a total solar eclipse, the Moon perfectly covers the Sun's bright disc, the sky goes dark in the middle of the day, and the Sun's faint outer atmosphere — called the corona — becomes visible as a glowing ring. Total solar eclipses only last a few minutes, and you can only see them from a narrow strip of land where the Moon's shadow falls. Anywhere else, you might see a partial eclipse where only part of the Sun is covered.\n\nIt is dangerous to look directly at the Sun, even during an eclipse, because the unblocked parts are still extremely bright. People use special eclipse glasses or pinhole projectors to watch safely.\n\nA lunar eclipse happens the other way around. The Moon passes through the shadow of the Earth. Because Earth is much bigger than the Moon, the shadow lasts longer — a lunar eclipse can take more than an hour. During a total lunar eclipse, the Moon does not vanish; instead it turns a deep coppery red. This is because the only sunlight reaching the Moon at that point has bent through Earth's atmosphere, which filters out the blue colours and lets the red light through. It is the same reason sunsets are red. Some people call a totally eclipsed Moon a 'blood moon'.\n\nSolar eclipses can only happen at new moon, and lunar eclipses can only happen at full moon. They do not happen every month because the Moon's orbit is tilted slightly, so usually the Moon passes a little above or below the Sun's line.\n\nAncient peoples often found eclipses frightening. Today we can predict them centuries in advance.","topics":["space","eclipse","sun","moon","corona"]}
{"id":"seed:en:tides","source":"seed:en:tides","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Tides are the slow rise and fall of the sea level along coastlines. In most places, the sea rises and falls twice each day. The main reason this happens is the Moon's gravity.\n\nGravity pulls all objects with mass toward each other. The Moon pulls on Earth, and Earth pulls on the Moon. The Moon is too far away to lift the solid rock of Earth's surface much, but it can tug on the oceans, which flow easily. On the side of Earth facing the Moon, the water is pulled into a slight bulge. On the opposite side of Earth, there is a second bulge — caused by the fact that the solid Earth is being pulled toward the Moon a little more strongly than the water on the far side, leaving the far-side water behind. As Earth spins, different coastlines pass through these two bulges, so most places see two high tides and two low tides each day.\n\nThe Sun also pulls on Earth's oceans. The Sun is much bigger than the Moon, but it is also much farther away, so its tide-raising effect is about half as strong. When the Sun, Moon, and Earth line up — at full moon and new moon — the Sun's pull adds to the Moon's, and the tides are bigger than usual. These are called spring tides (the name has nothing to do with the season). When the Sun and Moon pull at right angles to each other — at first quarter and last quarter — the tides are smaller. These are called neap tides.\n\nThe size of the tide also depends on the shape of the coast. In a long narrow bay, water can pile up much higher than on an open shore. The Bay of Fundy in Canada has the biggest tides on Earth — the sea level there can change by more than 16 metres between low and high tide.\n\nTides matter for ships, fishermen, and animals like crabs and seabirds that live where the sea meets the land.","topics":["space","tides","moon","gravity","oceans"]}
{"id":"seed:en:big-bang","source":"seed:en:big-bang","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"The Big Bang is the name for the beginning of the universe — the moment everything we can see started expanding from a hot, dense state about 13.8 billion years ago.\n\nThe name is a little misleading. The Big Bang was not an explosion in space, like a firework going off. It was the rapid expansion of space itself, everywhere all at once. There was no 'outside' for the early universe to expand into; space and time were both part of what was beginning.\n\nIn the very first moments, the universe was so hot and dense that ordinary atoms could not exist. As it expanded, it cooled. After a few minutes, simple atomic nuclei — hydrogen and helium — formed. Hundreds of thousands of years later, it had cooled enough for full atoms to form, and light could travel freely for the first time. That oldest light is still around today as a faint glow filling the whole sky in every direction. Astronomers call it the cosmic microwave background, and they study it carefully because it is like a baby picture of the universe.\n\nIt took hundreds of millions of years for gravity to pull the gas into the first stars and galaxies. Heavier elements like carbon, oxygen, and iron — the ones that make up planets and living bodies — were forged inside those stars and scattered when the stars exploded. Our Sun and Earth formed from the recycled remains of earlier generations of stars, about 4.6 billion years ago.\n\nThe universe is still expanding today. Astronomers can see this because galaxies that are far from us are moving away from us, and the more distant ones are moving away faster. To everyone's surprise, the expansion is also speeding up. The cause of this acceleration is mysterious; physicists call it dark energy and are still trying to understand what it is.\n\nThe Big Bang is the best explanation we have for why the universe looks the way it does. There are still many open questions, but the broad outline is supported by a lot of careful measurement.","topics":["space","universe","big bang","cosmology","dark energy"]}
# ─── Body cluster ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{"id":"seed:en:heart","source":"seed:en:heart","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"The heart is a muscle about the size of your fist, sitting in the middle of your chest, slightly to the left. Its job is to pump blood around your body, and it never stops — it beats around 100,000 times every day, every day of your life.\n\nThe heart has four chambers, like four small rooms. The two upper chambers are called atria; the two lower ones are called ventricles. Blood moves through the heart in a one-way loop, controlled by valves that snap shut so blood cannot flow backwards. The 'lub-dub' sound a doctor hears with a stethoscope is the sound of those valves closing.\n\nThe right side of the heart pumps blood that has just come back from the body — blood that has given its oxygen to your muscles and other organs and is carrying carbon dioxide instead. It sends that blood to the lungs, where the carbon dioxide is breathed out and fresh oxygen is picked up. The left side of the heart then pumps the oxygen-rich blood out to the rest of the body. The left side has to push harder, because it has to reach all the way to your fingers and toes, so its walls are thicker and stronger.\n\nWhen you run or climb stairs, your muscles need more oxygen, so your heart beats faster to deliver more blood. When you rest, it slows down again. You can feel your heartbeat as a pulse on the inside of your wrist or on the side of your neck — that is your blood being pushed by the heart through arteries close to the skin.\n\nA grown-up's heart pumps about 5 litres of blood every minute when resting, and several times that during hard exercise. Over a whole human life, that adds up to more than 200 million litres of blood — enough to fill more than 80 Olympic swimming pools.","topics":["body","heart","blood","circulation","muscles"]}
{"id":"seed:en:lungs-breathing","source":"seed:en:lungs-breathing","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Your lungs are two soft, spongy organs in your chest that handle breathing. Their job is to bring oxygen from the air into your blood and to send carbon dioxide back out. You cannot live more than a few minutes without them working.\n\nWhen you breathe in, a strong sheet of muscle below your lungs called the diaphragm pulls down, and the muscles between your ribs lift the rib cage out and up. This makes your chest bigger inside, and air rushes in through your nose or mouth to fill the extra space. The air travels down a tube called the trachea, then splits into two smaller tubes, one for each lung, and from there branches into thousands of tinier and tinier tubes — like the branches of an upside-down tree. At the very ends are tiny air sacs called alveoli. A grown-up has about 300 million of them. Spread out flat, they would cover an area larger than a tennis court.\n\nThe alveoli are surrounded by very thin blood vessels. Oxygen from the air slips through the alveoli wall into the blood. At the same time, carbon dioxide — which the body's cells make as a waste product — leaves the blood and enters the alveoli, ready to be breathed out. When you breathe out, the diaphragm relaxes and the rib cage drops, squeezing the lungs and pushing the air back out.\n\nYou breathe about 12 to 20 times a minute when resting, and faster when running or excited. Most of the time you do not have to think about it; the brain stem keeps it going automatically, even when you sleep.\n\nThe air you breathe in is mostly nitrogen, with about 21% oxygen. The air you breathe out has less oxygen and more carbon dioxide and water vapour. That is why your breath fogs up a cold window: the water in it cools down and turns to mist.","topics":["body","lungs","breathing","oxygen","alveoli"]}
{"id":"seed:en:brain","source":"seed:en:brain","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"The brain is the control centre of your body. It sits inside your skull, protected by hard bone, and it is responsible for everything you think, feel, remember, see, hear, and do. Even when you are asleep, your brain stays busy.\n\nThe brain is made of about 86 billion nerve cells called neurons. Neurons send signals to each other using tiny pulses of electricity and small chemical messengers. Each neuron can connect to thousands of others, so the whole brain is a fantastically complicated network. Many of the things you can do — recognising a face, riding a bike, understanding a sentence — depend on patterns of activity flowing through that network.\n\nThe brain has different parts that do different jobs. The wrinkled outer layer is called the cerebral cortex; this is where most of your thinking, planning, and language happen. Different patches of the cortex handle different things: one part processes what your eyes are seeing, another part controls the movement of your muscles, another part stores memories. Deeper inside, the cerebellum at the back helps with balance and smooth movement, and the brain stem keeps things like breathing and heartbeat going automatically.\n\nLeft and right halves of the brain do slightly different things. In most people, the left half is more involved in language and step-by-step reasoning, while the right is more involved in spatial sense and recognising patterns. The two halves talk to each other constantly through a thick bundle of fibres called the corpus callosum.\n\nYour brain uses about 20% of all the energy your body burns, even though it weighs only about 1.4 kilograms. It is a very hungry organ. It runs on glucose (a sugar) and oxygen, both delivered by blood. If the blood supply is cut off for even a few minutes, brain cells start to die.\n\nBrains keep changing throughout life. Every time you learn something new, the connections between your neurons rewire a little. That is what learning is.","topics":["body","brain","neurons","nervous system","memory"]}
{"id":"seed:en:digestion","source":"seed:en:digestion","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Digestion is how your body breaks food down into small pieces that can be used to power your cells, build new tissue, and grow. The whole journey from mouth to the other end takes about 24 to 72 hours.\n\nDigestion starts in the mouth. Your teeth grind food into smaller bits, and a watery liquid called saliva mixes with it. Saliva contains an enzyme — a special protein that speeds up chemical reactions — that begins breaking down starches even before you swallow.\n\nWhen you swallow, the chewed food slides down a muscular tube called the oesophagus into the stomach. The stomach is a stretchy bag that mixes the food with strong acid and more enzymes. The acid is so strong it would burn your skin, but the stomach has a thick layer of mucus to protect itself. Inside the stomach, food is churned into a thick soup.\n\nThe soup then enters the small intestine, a long curling tube about 6 metres long in adults. Most of the actual digesting happens here. Juices from the pancreas and bile from the liver pour in and finish breaking down the proteins, fats, and carbohydrates. The walls of the small intestine are covered in millions of tiny finger-like bumps called villi, which absorb the nutrients into the blood.\n\nWhat the body cannot use moves on into the large intestine. Here, water is pulled back into the body, and trillions of friendly bacteria help digest some of the leftovers. The remaining waste is stored briefly and then leaves the body as poo.\n\nDifferent foods are digested at different speeds. A glass of water passes through quickly. A meal heavy in fat and meat takes much longer. The liver, which sits just under the right side of the rib cage, also plays a huge role: it cleans the blood that comes from the gut and stores energy as a substance called glycogen, ready for when you need it.","topics":["body","digestion","stomach","intestine","liver"]}
{"id":"seed:en:skeleton-bones","source":"seed:en:skeleton-bones","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Your skeleton is the framework of bones inside your body. It does several jobs at once: it gives your body its shape, it lets you stand up against gravity, it protects soft organs like the brain and heart, and it gives your muscles something to pull on so you can move.\n\nA grown-up has 206 bones. Babies are actually born with more — around 270 — but several pairs of small bones fuse together as they grow up. The biggest bone is the femur, the long bone in the upper leg. The smallest are three tiny bones inside each ear, the smallest of which is no bigger than a grain of rice.\n\nBones are not dead, dry sticks like the ones in a museum. They are living tissue, full of blood vessels and constantly being rebuilt. The outside is hard and dense, made mostly of a mineral called calcium phosphate that gives it strength. The inside of many bones contains a soft, spongy tissue called bone marrow. Marrow is where your body makes new red blood cells (which carry oxygen) and white blood cells (which fight germs). About two million new red blood cells are produced in your marrow every second.\n\nWhere two bones meet, there is a joint. Most joints let the bones move against each other, in different ways. The hinge joints in your fingers, knees, and elbows swing back and forth. The ball-and-socket joints in your shoulders and hips can swing in almost any direction. To stop the bone surfaces from grinding, joints are lined with smooth cartilage and oiled with a slippery liquid.\n\nIf you break a bone, the body slowly grows new bone tissue across the gap to seal it back together. That is why a cast just has to hold the bone still for a few weeks while it heals itself.\n\nEating foods with calcium — like milk, cheese, beans, and leafy greens — and getting outside for some sunlight helps build strong bones.","topics":["body","skeleton","bones","joints","marrow"]}
{"id":"seed:en:muscles","source":"seed:en:muscles","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Muscles are the parts of your body that produce movement. Whenever you walk, smile, blink, swallow, or even just sit up against gravity, muscles are doing the work. Your body has more than 600 of them, and they make up about a third of your weight.\n\nThere are three different kinds. Skeletal muscles are the ones attached to your bones. These are the muscles you can move on purpose — biceps, calves, the muscles in your face. Smooth muscles line the inside of your stomach, your blood vessels, and other organs; they squeeze without you having to think about it. Cardiac muscle is found only in the heart, and it is built to keep beating non-stop your whole life without getting tired.\n\nA muscle works by getting shorter. It cannot push, only pull. That is why muscles usually come in opposing pairs: one to bend a joint, and another to straighten it. When you bend your arm, your biceps shortens and pulls your forearm up; the triceps on the back of the arm relaxes and stretches. To straighten your arm again, the triceps shortens and the biceps relaxes.\n\nAt the microscopic level, a muscle is made of bundles of tiny fibres. Inside each fibre are even smaller filaments that slide past each other when the muscle is told to contract. The signal to contract comes from the brain along nerves, ending in a small chemical pulse that triggers the slide.\n\nMuscles need fuel — sugar and oxygen, delivered by blood — to do their work. When you exercise hard for a long time, your muscles can run low on oxygen and produce a substance called lactate, which is part of why they start to ache. Rest and water help them recover.\n\nMuscles also get stronger with regular use. The more you ask them to do (within reason), the more your body builds them up. Stop using them, and they shrink — astronauts in space have to exercise every day to keep their muscles from wasting.","topics":["body","muscles","movement","skeletal","exercise"]}
{"id":"seed:en:skin","source":"seed:en:skin","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Your skin is the largest organ in your body. If you could spread it out flat, it would cover about 2 square metres on a grown-up. It is a stretchy, waterproof, self-repairing barrier between you and the outside world.\n\nSkin has several layers. The thin outer layer you can see is called the epidermis. It is mostly made of dead, flattened cells packed tightly together, which makes it tough and helps keep germs and water out. New cells are constantly being made at the bottom of the epidermis and pushed upwards as older cells flake off. You actually shed about 30,000 to 40,000 dead skin cells every minute. A lot of household dust is old skin.\n\nUnderneath is a thicker layer called the dermis. This is where the action happens. The dermis contains tiny blood vessels, nerve endings that let you feel touch, pressure, heat, cold, and pain, sweat glands that cool you down by releasing water, oil glands that keep the skin from drying out, and the roots of your hairs. Below the dermis is a layer of fat that helps keep you warm and cushions you from bumps.\n\nSkin colour comes from a substance called melanin, made by special cells in the epidermis. People whose ancestors lived in places with strong sunlight tend to have more melanin, because melanin protects skin from the harmful parts of sunlight. Even pale skin makes more melanin when it gets a lot of sun, which is what a tan is.\n\nWhen you cut yourself, the skin starts repairing itself almost immediately. Tiny blood cells called platelets clump together to plug the leak, then white blood cells clean out any germs, and the skin slowly grows new tissue across the gap. Small cuts heal in days. Big ones leave scars, which are skin grown back in a slightly different pattern.\n\nSkin also helps make vitamin D when sunlight hits it. Vitamin D is important for strong bones.","topics":["body","skin","epidermis","dermis","sweat"]}
{"id":"seed:en:immune-system","source":"seed:en:immune-system","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"The immune system is your body's defence system against germs — the bacteria, viruses, and other tiny invaders that can make you ill. It works around the clock, mostly without you noticing.\n\nThe first line of defence is simple: keep germs out. Your skin is a tough barrier. Tears, saliva, and the mucus in your nose contain chemicals that kill many germs on contact. The strong acid in your stomach destroys most of the germs that arrive in your food.\n\nIf germs do get through, the second line of defence kicks in. White blood cells, made in your bone marrow, patrol your body in the bloodstream. Some kinds of white blood cells eat invading germs whole. Others release alarm signals that bring more help to the spot. The redness, warmth, and swelling around a cut or splinter is your body sending blood and white cells to fight the infection.\n\nThe most clever part is the third line of defence: the adaptive immune system. Special white cells called lymphocytes can learn to recognise specific germs and remember them. Once they have met a particular germ, they make tiny y-shaped molecules called antibodies that lock onto that germ and mark it for destruction. The next time the same germ shows up, your body recognises it instantly and wipes it out before you ever feel sick. That is why most childhood illnesses, like chickenpox, you can only catch once.\n\nVaccines work by giving the immune system a safe practice run. A vaccine shows your body harmless pieces of a germ — or a weakened version that cannot make you ill — so your immune system learns to recognise it. Then if the real germ ever turns up, you are already protected.\n\nSometimes the immune system makes mistakes. If it overreacts to harmless things like pollen or peanuts, you get an allergy. If it attacks your own healthy cells, you get an autoimmune disease. Doctors can often help by calming the immune system down.","topics":["body","immune","white blood cells","antibodies","vaccines"]}
{"id":"seed:en:eyes-sight","source":"seed:en:eyes-sight","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Eyes are how you see. They turn the light bouncing off the world into signals your brain can understand. Each eye is roughly the size of a ping-pong ball and sits in a bony socket in your skull, padded with a little fat to cushion it.\n\nLight enters your eye through a clear, curved layer at the front called the cornea. The cornea bends the light, doing most of the focusing. Behind it is a coloured ring called the iris — the part that gives an eye its blue, brown, or green colour. The iris has a hole in the middle called the pupil. The iris muscles can make the pupil bigger in dim light to let more light in, and smaller in bright light to let less in. That is why pupils look small in sunshine and big in a dark room.\n\nBehind the iris sits a flexible lens. Tiny muscles around the lens squeeze it thicker for looking at near things and let it relax thinner for looking at far things. This fine-tuning is called focusing. The lens projects an upside-down image onto the back of the eye, the retina. The brain flips the image right-way-up later.\n\nThe retina is a thin sheet covered in millions of light-sensitive cells of two main types. Rods work in dim light and only see in shades of grey, which is why colours fade at night. Cones work in bright light and come in three types — sensitive to roughly red, green, and blue light — which is what gives you colour vision. The retina sends its signals down a thick cable called the optic nerve, straight to the back of the brain.\n\nIf the eyeball is slightly the wrong shape, the image lands a little in front of or behind the retina, and things look blurry. Glasses or contact lenses correct this by bending the light a bit before it enters the eye.\n\nYou blink about 15 to 20 times every minute, mostly without noticing, to keep the cornea moist and clean.","topics":["body","eyes","sight","retina","vision"]}
{"id":"seed:en:ears-hearing","source":"seed:en:ears-hearing","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Hearing is how you sense sound. Sound itself is just a tiny rapid wobble in the air — a sound wave — usually made when something vibrates, like a guitar string, a person's vocal cords, or a clapping pair of hands. Your ears catch those wobbles and turn them into signals your brain can understand.\n\nEach ear has three parts. The outer ear is the bit you can see, plus a short tunnel that leads inward. The funny shape of the outer ear helps gather sound and lets you tell roughly where a noise came from. Sound waves travel down the tunnel and bump into the eardrum, a thin tight piece of skin stretched across the end like the skin of a drum. When sound waves hit it, the eardrum vibrates.\n\nBehind the eardrum is the middle ear, which contains the three smallest bones in the body. They are sometimes nicknamed the hammer, anvil, and stirrup because of their shapes. The vibrations of the eardrum pass through these three bones, which act like tiny levers, making the vibrations stronger.\n\nThe last bone passes the vibrations into the inner ear, where the real magic happens. The inner ear contains a snail-shaped tube called the cochlea, filled with fluid and lined with thousands of tiny hairs. As the vibrations ripple through the fluid, different hairs bend at different frequencies — some only when high notes come through, others only for low notes. Each bending hair sends a signal up the auditory nerve to your brain, which puts it all together into the sounds you recognise as speech, music, or footsteps.\n\nThe inner ear also has three little loops of fluid that have nothing to do with hearing. They are how you sense balance: as you tilt your head, the fluid sloshes and tells your brain which way is up. That is why a bad ear infection can make you dizzy.\n\nLoud sounds can damage the tiny hairs in the cochlea, and damaged hairs do not grow back, so loud noises should be kept brief.","topics":["body","ears","hearing","cochlea","balance"]}
{"id":"seed:en:sleep-dreams","source":"seed:en:sleep-dreams","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Everyone needs to sleep. Babies sleep about 16 hours a day, children 9 to 11 hours, and most grown-ups around 7 to 9. Going without sleep makes you grumpy and clumsy, and going for many days without it can make you very ill. But why we need it so much is still being studied.\n\nWhat we do know is that a sleeping brain is not a switched-off brain. It is doing important work. While you sleep, your body releases hormones that help you grow and repair small bits of damage. Your immune system makes new disease-fighting cells. And your brain seems to sort through what happened during the day, strengthening some memories and quietly throwing others away. People who get good sleep before a test do better than people who do not.\n\nSleep happens in cycles, each about 90 minutes long. Inside each cycle there are stages that go from light dozing, to deep sleep where your body is very still and your brain waves are slow, and finally to a stage called REM (which stands for rapid eye movement). During REM, your eyes flick around under closed lids, your breathing speeds up, and your brain becomes almost as active as when you are awake. Most vivid dreams happen in REM.\n\nDreams are stories the sleeping brain makes for itself, often using bits of recent memories stitched together in strange new ways. They can feel completely real while you are inside them, and most are forgotten within minutes of waking. Why brains dream is still one of science's open questions. One idea is that dreams help practise emotions and rehearse situations safely. Another is that they are a side effect of the brain reorganising memories.\n\nNearly every animal we have studied seems to sleep, including fish, insects, and even simple worms. Some birds and dolphins sleep one half of the brain at a time so they can keep flying or swimming.\n\nA dark, quiet, cool room and a regular bedtime help most people sleep well.","topics":["body","sleep","dreams","rem","memory"]}
# ─── How-things-work cluster ───────────────────────────────────────────────
{"id":"seed:en:magnets","source":"seed:en:magnets","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"A magnet is something that pulls on certain metals — most famously iron — without touching them. The pulling region around a magnet is called its magnetic field. You cannot see a magnetic field directly, but you can reveal its shape by sprinkling iron filings on a piece of paper laid over a magnet: the filings line up along curved lines running from one end of the magnet to the other.\n\nEvery magnet has two ends called poles, named north and south. Two like poles push each other away (north pushes north, south pushes south), and two unlike poles pull each other together. If you cut a magnet in half, you do not get one north and one south on their own — you get two smaller magnets, each with its own pair of poles.\n\nMagnetism comes from electrons, the tiny particles that orbit inside atoms. Every spinning electron is itself a microscopic magnet. In most materials, the electrons are arranged so their tiny magnetic effects cancel out. In iron, nickel, cobalt, and a few other metals, the electrons can line up so their effects add together, and the whole lump becomes magnetic.\n\nEarth itself is a giant magnet. Deep inside the planet, hot liquid iron flows around the solid core, and that flow generates a magnetic field big enough to surround the whole planet. A compass needle is a small magnet free to spin; it lines up with Earth's field and points roughly north.\n\nMoving electricity also makes a magnetic field. If you wrap a wire into a coil and run an electric current through it, the coil acts like a magnet — and you can switch it off again by switching the current off. Such an electromagnet is what makes electric motors, doorbells, and the lifting magnets in scrapyards work.\n\nSo magnets and electricity are deeply linked: each can produce the other. This connection is one of the most useful discoveries in all of science.","topics":["how-things-work","magnets","magnetic field","poles","electromagnetism"]}
{"id":"seed:en:electricity","source":"seed:en:electricity","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Electricity is the movement of tiny charged particles, usually electrons. Atoms are made of a heavy nucleus surrounded by a cloud of electrons. In metals like copper, some of those electrons are loosely held and can drift from atom to atom. When huge numbers of them drift in the same direction, you have an electric current — what we mean in everyday talk by 'electricity flowing'.\n\nElectricity needs a complete loop, called a circuit, to flow. A simple torch (flashlight) is a circuit: a battery pushes electrons out of one end, through a wire, through the bulb (where they make the filament so hot it glows), and back into the other end of the battery. Break the loop anywhere — say, with a switch — and the flow stops.\n\nThe push that makes electrons move is called voltage and is measured in volts. The amount of flow is called current and is measured in amperes (amps). Putting them together gives power — how fast electrical energy is being used — measured in watts. A small LED bulb might use a few watts; a kettle, more than a thousand.\n\nMaterials that let electrons move easily are called conductors. Most metals are good conductors. Materials that block the flow are called insulators. Plastic, rubber, dry wood, and glass are all insulators. The plastic coating around an electrical cord is there to stop you (and other things) from accidentally becoming part of the circuit.\n\nElectricity in your home arrives from a power station along thick wires. In most countries the supply is alternating current (AC), which means the electrons wobble back and forth many times a second rather than flowing steadily one way. Batteries instead supply direct current (DC), where electrons flow steadily in one direction.\n\nElectricity is dangerous because the human body is a conductor. A current of even a small fraction of an amp through the heart can be deadly. That is why mains sockets are insulated and why you should never poke metal objects into them.","topics":["how-things-work","electricity","circuit","voltage","current"]}
{"id":"seed:en:batteries","source":"seed:en:batteries","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"A battery is a small package that stores energy in chemicals and releases it as electricity. Inside, a battery has two different materials — called the anode and the cathode — separated by a third substance called an electrolyte. Chemical reactions between these materials let electrons pile up on one side (the negative end, marked −) and not the other (the positive end, marked +). When you connect the two ends through a wire, electrons rush from − to + through the wire, and that flow is the current that lights your torch or runs your toy.\n\nDifferent battery chemistries do this in different ways. A standard alkaline battery uses zinc and manganese dioxide, with a potassium hydroxide paste as the electrolyte. The chemical reactions slowly use up the zinc, and once enough is used the battery is flat and goes in the bin. Lithium-ion batteries — the kind in phones, laptops, and electric cars — use lithium ions sliding back and forth between two layered materials. The big advantage is that you can run the reaction backwards by pushing electricity in the other way, which is what charging means. That is why some batteries are rechargeable and others are not.\n\nThe voltage of a single battery cell is set by the chemistry. An alkaline cell is about 1.5 volts; a lithium-ion cell about 3.7. To get higher voltages, cells are stacked in a row inside a single case. A 9-volt battery, for example, has six small 1.5-volt cells inside.\n\nBatteries do not 'store electricity' in the way a bucket stores water. They store chemical energy that is released as electricity only when a circuit is connected. That is also why a battery left unused for years still mostly works: the chemicals are slow to react if there is no path for the electrons.\n\nUsed batteries should be recycled, not thrown in the rubbish, because they contain metals and chemicals that can leak and pollute the soil.","topics":["how-things-work","batteries","chemistry","lithium","rechargeable"]}
{"id":"seed:en:simple-machines","source":"seed:en:simple-machines","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"A simple machine is a basic tool that makes a job easier by changing how a force is applied. Simple machines do not give you energy for free — you still have to push or pull. What they do is let you trade a smaller force over a longer distance for a larger force over a shorter distance.\n\nThere are six classic simple machines. A lever is a stiff bar resting on a pivot called a fulcrum. Push down on the long side and the short side lifts a much heavier load. A seesaw is a lever, and so is a crowbar prying open a lid. A wheel and axle is a small wheel attached to a larger one; turning the big wheel applies a stronger turning force to the small one — that is how a steering wheel and a doorknob work.\n\nA pulley is a rope running over a wheel; it changes the direction of a pull, so you can lift a load by pulling down. With several pulleys, you can lift a heavy weight by pulling a longer length of rope with less force.\n\nAn inclined plane is just a ramp. Pushing a heavy box up a long gentle slope is easier than lifting it straight up the same height. A wedge is a moving inclined plane — knife blades and axes are wedges, sliding through wood or food and pushing it apart sideways. A screw is a long thin inclined plane wrapped around a cylinder; turning it many times advances it forward a little for each turn, with much greater force than a straight push.\n\nGears are wheels with teeth that lock into each other. When a small gear drives a big gear, it spins slower but turns with more force; when a big gear drives a small one, the small one spins faster but with less force. Bicycles, clocks, and car gearboxes all use gears to trade speed for force or the other way around.\n\nMost everyday machines are clever combinations of these few basics.","topics":["how-things-work","levers","pulleys","gears","simple machines"]}
{"id":"seed:en:sound","source":"seed:en:sound","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Sound is what you hear when something vibrates fast enough to wobble the air. A vibrating object — a guitar string, a person's vocal cords, a clapping hand — pushes the air molecules right next to it back and forth. Those molecules bump the next molecules, which bump the next, and a wave of pressure ripples outwards in every direction. When the wave reaches your ears, the eardrum vibrates, and your brain interprets the signal as sound.\n\nSound waves need something to travel through. They go through air, water, wood, and metal — usually faster the denser the material. They cannot travel through empty space. That is why, if a clock alarm went off on the Moon (which has no air), no microphone there would pick it up.\n\nIn dry air at room temperature, sound travels about 343 metres a second. That is fast for everyday life but very slow compared to light, which is why you see lightning before you hear thunder. Counting the seconds between the flash and the rumble tells you roughly how far away the storm is: every three seconds is about one kilometre.\n\nThe pitch of a sound — how high or low it sounds — depends on the frequency of the wave, which is how many wobbles happen per second. Frequency is measured in hertz (Hz). A low rumble might be 100 Hz; a high whistle, 5000 Hz or more. Children can usually hear from about 20 to 20,000 Hz; that range shrinks slowly as people get older. Bats and dogs hear far higher than humans; whales and elephants make sounds far lower.\n\nThe loudness of a sound depends on the amplitude of the wave — how big the back-and-forth wobble is. Loudness is measured in decibels (dB). A whisper is around 30 dB; normal talk, 60; a busy road, 80; a rock concert, 110. Sounds above about 85 dB for long periods can damage the tiny hairs in the inner ear permanently.","topics":["how-things-work","sound","waves","frequency","pitch"]}
{"id":"seed:en:light","source":"seed:en:light","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Light is the form of energy that lets us see. It travels in straight lines through empty space at about 300,000 kilometres per second — the fastest anything can go. Sunlight takes only about 8 minutes to reach Earth from the Sun, even though the Sun is 150 million kilometres away.\n\nLight behaves both like a wave and like a stream of tiny packets. The packets are called photons. The wave picture explains things like the way light spreads out and bends; the photon picture explains how light gives up its energy in chunks when it lands on, say, a leaf or your eye.\n\nWhat we call white light from the Sun is actually a mixture of all the colours of the rainbow. Each colour is light of a slightly different wavelength — red has the longest wavelength of visible light, violet the shortest. When white light passes through raindrops, the drops bend each colour by a slightly different amount and the colours separate, which is what produces a rainbow. The same trick can be done with a triangular glass prism.\n\nThere is more light than just the colours we can see. Beyond red is infrared, which we feel as heat from a stove or a person's body. Beyond violet is ultraviolet, which gives sunburn. Further still are X-rays and radio waves. They are all the same kind of thing — electromagnetic waves — just at different wavelengths.\n\nWhen light hits an object, three things can happen. Some of the light may be absorbed and turned into heat (which is why dark clothes get hot in the sun). Some may bounce off, called reflection. Some may pass through if the material is clear, called transmission, and along the way it can bend, called refraction. The colour you see when you look at something is the colours of light it does not absorb, bouncing back to your eyes. A red apple is red because it absorbs most colours and reflects red.\n\nNothing in the universe is faster than light in empty space.","topics":["how-things-work","light","photons","wavelength","colour"]}
{"id":"seed:en:mirrors-lenses","source":"seed:en:mirrors-lenses","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Mirrors and lenses both reshape where light goes, but they do it in different ways. A mirror reflects light off its smooth surface; a lens lets light pass through but bends it on the way.\n\nFor a flat mirror, the rule is simple: the angle the light comes in at equals the angle it leaves at, both measured from a line standing straight up out of the surface. That is why your reflection looks the same size as you do, just left-right swapped. A curved mirror works the same way at every tiny patch, but because the surface curves, light from a single direction is gathered or spread out. A concave mirror (curving inwards, like the inside of a bowl) can focus parallel sunbeams down to a hot spot — large concave mirrors are used in some telescopes to gather starlight. A convex mirror (curving outwards) spreads light out instead, giving a wide-angle view: that is why the side mirrors on a car often look slightly bulged.\n\nLenses bend light by refraction. Light slows down a little when it enters glass or clear plastic and speeds up again when it leaves, and at any tilted surface this change of speed twists the path. A convex lens (thicker in the middle than at the edges) bends parallel light rays inwards so they cross at a focal point — this is how a magnifying glass can set paper on fire by focusing the Sun, and how the lens in your eye throws an image onto the retina.\n\nA concave lens (thinner in the middle) does the opposite: it spreads parallel rays outwards. Glasses for short-sighted people use concave lenses; glasses for long-sighted people use convex ones, each undoing a slight focusing problem of the eye.\n\nTelescopes, microscopes, cameras, and projectors all use combinations of mirrors and lenses. By stacking several lenses in a row, optical designers can correct distortions and produce sharp images of things very far away or very small.","topics":["how-things-work","mirrors","lenses","reflection","refraction"]}
{"id":"seed:en:fire","source":"seed:en:fire","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Fire is what happens when something burns. Burning is a fast chemical reaction between a fuel and oxygen from the air. The reaction releases lots of heat and light, which is why a fire feels warm and looks bright.\n\nFire needs three things at the same time: fuel, oxygen, and enough heat to get the reaction started. Fire safety experts call this the fire triangle. Take any one of those three things away and the fire goes out. A blanket smothers a small flame by cutting off oxygen. Pouring water cools the fuel below its ignition temperature. A firefighter chopping a fire break clears away the fuel.\n\nDifferent fuels need different amounts of heat to start. A piece of paper catches at quite a low temperature; a thick log needs a lot more energy to get going. That is why people start a campfire with newspaper and small twigs first, then add bigger and bigger pieces.\n\nA flame is the glowing region of hot gas just above the fuel. When wood burns, the heat first cooks the wood, releasing flammable gases. It is those gases — not the wood itself — that catch fire and form the flame. Glowing red embers, on the other hand, are solid fuel reacting directly with oxygen at the surface, without a flame.\n\nThe colour of a flame depends on its temperature and on what is burning. A candle flame is mostly yellow because tiny soot particles inside it are glowing hot. A gas stove flame is mostly blue because the gas burns more cleanly and at a higher temperature. Adding certain salts produces other colours; this is what makes fireworks green, red, or purple.\n\nFire is enormously useful — for cooking, for keeping warm, and historically for making metal tools — but it spreads very quickly when fuel and oxygen are plentiful. That is why every home should have working smoke alarms and a clear plan for getting out if something catches fire.","topics":["how-things-work","fire","combustion","oxygen","fuel"]}
{"id":"seed:en:ice-water","source":"seed:en:ice-water","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Water is unusual among everyday substances because its solid form, ice, is less dense than the liquid. That is why ice cubes float and why ponds freeze from the top down. For most other materials, the solid sinks in its own liquid.\n\nThe trick is in the shape of the water molecule. Each water molecule is one oxygen atom bonded to two hydrogen atoms, with a slight bend between them. The molecule has a weakly positive side near the hydrogens and a weakly negative side near the oxygen, so each molecule pulls on its neighbours. In liquid water, the molecules tumble around freely, sometimes close together and sometimes farther apart, but on average packed in fairly tight. As water cools toward 0 °C, the molecules slow down enough to settle into an open hexagonal pattern — a kind of crystal. That pattern keeps the molecules a little farther apart than they were in the liquid, so the same amount of water now fills more space. Less mass per litre means lower density, so the ice floats.\n\nThis quirk has huge consequences. Floating ice insulates the water below it: even when the air above a lake is far below freezing, the deep water stays at about 4 °C, and fish and other life can survive the winter. If ice sank, lakes would freeze solid from the bottom up and few water creatures would ever live through a cold winter.\n\nWater itself behaves strangely in another way: it stays liquid over a wide range of temperatures (0–100 °C at sea level), making it the perfect medium for life chemistry. The molecule's slight stickiness also lets water pull itself up tall and thin tubes, which is part of how trees move water from roots to leaves.\n\nWater can be in three states — solid (ice), liquid, and gas (water vapour) — and switches between them without changing what it is. The same molecules that fall as snowflakes in winter may evaporate from a puddle in summer.","topics":["how-things-work","water","ice","density","molecule"]}
{"id":"seed:en:salt","source":"seed:en:salt","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Salt is a chemical called sodium chloride. Each tiny salt crystal is built from billions of pairs of two atoms — sodium and chlorine — locked together in a neat cubic pattern. If you look closely at table salt with a magnifying glass, you can see that the grains really are little cubes.\n\nWhen salt dissolves in water, the sodium and chlorine atoms come apart from each other and drift off into the water, surrounded by water molecules. They no longer sit in their crystal pattern; they wander freely. That is why dissolved salt is invisible — the bits are smaller than the wavelengths of light. The salt is still there, of course, as you can confirm by tasting the water or by letting the water evaporate, leaving the salt behind.\n\nDissolving salt in water actually changes the water's behaviour. Salt water freezes at a lower temperature than fresh water — for example, at about −2 °C instead of 0 °C — because the dissolved salt particles get in the way of the water molecules trying to lock into a crystal. This is why people sprinkle salt on icy roads in winter: it lowers the freezing point so the ice melts even when the air is still below 0 °C.\n\nSalt also makes water slightly heavier (denser), which is one reason it is easier to float in the sea than in a swimming pool, and why an egg that sinks in fresh water will float in very salty water.\n\nLiving things — including you — need a small amount of salt to work properly. Sodium and chlorine ions help nerves send signals and help muscles contract. Most people get more than enough salt from food, and too much salt over many years is hard on the heart and kidneys.\n\nMost of the world's salt comes from one of two places: from seawater dried in shallow ponds, and from underground deposits left by ancient seas that dried up millions of years ago.","topics":["how-things-work","salt","sodium chloride","dissolving","freezing point"]}
{"id":"seed:en:soap","source":"seed:en:soap","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Soap is so good at cleaning because of the special shape of its molecules. A soap molecule has two ends that behave very differently. One end likes water — chemists call it hydrophilic, which is Greek for water-loving. The other end avoids water but happily mixes with oil and fat — hydrophobic, water-fearing.\n\nMost dirt that sticks to your skin or your clothes is held there by oil. Sweat, kitchen grease, and even the layer of natural oil your skin produces are all hard to wash away with plain water, because oil and water do not mix. This is why washing your hands with cold water alone usually does not get the grease off.\n\nWhen you add soap, things change. The soap molecules arrange themselves with their water-loving ends pointing into the water and their oil-loving ends digging into the oily dirt. The dirt gets surrounded by little balls of soap molecules called micelles — picture a hollow sphere with hairy oily insides and a smooth water-friendly outside. Once a blob of grease is wrapped up in a micelle, it can drift around in the water like any other tiny particle, and the rinse water carries it away.\n\nSoap also helps when fighting germs. Many germs, including the viruses that cause colds and flu, are wrapped in a thin oily coat. The oily ends of soap molecules pry into that coat and break it apart, killing the virus or making it useless. That is why properly washing hands with soap and water for around 20 seconds is one of the simplest and most powerful ways to stop disease.\n\nReal soap is made by mixing fats or oils with a strong alkali — traditionally lye, made from wood ash. The alkali splits the fat molecules into pieces, one of which is the soap. People have made soap this way for at least 5000 years.\n\nMost modern detergents are not soap but related molecules with the same two-ended trick.","topics":["how-things-work","soap","molecules","cleaning","hygiene"]}
# ─── Life cluster ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
{"id":"seed:en:photosynthesis","source":"seed:en:photosynthesis","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Photosynthesis is how plants make their own food. The word comes from Greek and means 'putting together with light'. Plants do not eat the way animals do; they take simple ingredients from the air, the soil, and sunlight, and combine them into sugars they can use as food and as building material.\n\nThe ingredients are easy to list. Plants pull water up from the ground through their roots. They take a gas called carbon dioxide out of the air through tiny holes on their leaves called stomata. And they catch sunlight using a green substance called chlorophyll, which is packed into the leaves and gives them their colour.\n\nInside the leaf, the energy of sunlight is used to rearrange the atoms of water and carbon dioxide into sugar (glucose) and oxygen. The plant keeps the sugar — using it as fuel and as the raw material for new leaves, stems, roots, flowers, and fruit. The oxygen is released back into the air. Almost all the oxygen you have ever breathed was put there by plants and tiny ocean plant-like creatures called algae.\n\nThis is why forests, grasslands, and oceans are so important. Without photosynthesis, animals (including us) would have nothing to eat and no oxygen to breathe. Photosynthesis is also how plants take carbon dioxide out of the air, which is one of the reasons protecting plants matters in a warming climate.\n\nWhen plants are eaten, the energy stored in their sugars passes on. A cow that eats grass is using sunlight that the grass captured weeks earlier. A child who drinks the cow's milk is using that same sunlight, two steps removed. The energy that powers nearly all life on Earth ultimately comes from the Sun, through photosynthesis.\n\nPhotosynthesis runs only when there is light, so plants stop making new sugar at night. They keep using their stored sugar to grow and stay alive in the dark.","topics":["life","photosynthesis","plants","chlorophyll","oxygen"]}
{"id":"seed:en:seeds-germination","source":"seed:en:seeds-germination","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"A seed is a tiny package of life. Inside its tough outer coat, a seed contains a baby plant — already shaped, with a small root and a small shoot — together with a store of food to feed it until it can make its own food by photosynthesis. Seeds can stay dormant, doing almost nothing, for months or even thousands of years, waiting for the right conditions to grow.\n\nWhen a seed lands in damp warm soil, it germinates. Water soaks into the seed and softens the coat. The baby plant inside swells and pushes out. The first thing to emerge is the root, which grows downwards into the soil — pulled by gravity, no matter which way the seed was lying. The root anchors the plant and starts pulling in water and minerals.\n\nNext, a shoot pushes upwards toward the light. The shoot uses the food stored in the seed to grow tall enough to break out of the soil. Once the first leaves unfold, they catch sunlight and begin photosynthesis, and the plant can feed itself. The original food store is used up, and the plant is on its own.\n\nDifferent seeds need different conditions. Some need only warmth and water. Some need to be cooled for weeks first — a kind of natural reminder that winter has passed. Some only sprout after a fire has cleared the ground above them.\n\nPlants spread their seeds in many clever ways. Dandelion seeds float on tiny parachutes. Sycamore seeds spin like helicopters on the wind. Burrs hook onto fur and travel with passing animals. Coconuts can drift across oceans. Some plants make tasty fruit so that animals will eat them and drop the seeds, well-fertilised, far away. Other plants explode their seed pods to fling them in all directions.\n\nA single oak tree can drop thousands of acorns in one autumn. Most will never sprout, but a few will, and a forest renews itself.","topics":["life","seeds","germination","plants","reproduction"]}
{"id":"seed:en:food-chains","source":"seed:en:food-chains","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"A food chain is a way of showing who eats whom in a place. Every food chain starts with sunlight and ends with the recycling of dead things back into the soil.\n\nAt the bottom of nearly every food chain on Earth are the producers — plants and plant-like organisms that make their own food from sunlight using photosynthesis. In the sea, the producers are mostly tiny floating algae called phytoplankton. On land, they are grasses, trees, and other plants.\n\nNext come the consumers, animals that cannot make their own food and so must eat. Plant-eating consumers — herbivores like cows, rabbits, and caterpillars — eat the producers. Meat-eaters — carnivores like wolves, sharks, and spiders — eat other animals. In between are omnivores, like humans, bears, and chickens, who eat both plants and animals.\n\nAt each step, energy is passed up the chain, but a lot is lost as body heat or used to power the animal's own movement and breathing. Roughly only a tenth of the energy at one level reaches the next. That is why there are usually far fewer top predators than herbivores: there is simply not enough energy left at the top of the chain to support many of them.\n\nA simple food chain might be: grass → grasshopper → frog → snake → hawk. In real life it is rarely that tidy. Most animals eat several different things and are eaten by several different others, so all the chains in a habitat tangle together into a food web.\n\nThe last group is the decomposers — bacteria, fungi, earthworms — that eat dead plants and animals and break them back down into simple substances that plants can use again. Without decomposers, the soil would run out of nutrients and the world would pile up with corpses.\n\nIf any link in a food web is removed — say, all the grass dies in a drought — every creature that depended on it suffers, and so do the creatures that ate them.","topics":["life","food chain","ecosystem","predator","decomposer"]}
{"id":"seed:en:cells","source":"seed:en:cells","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"A cell is the smallest unit of life. Every living thing on Earth — every bacterium, every blade of grass, every elephant, every person — is made of cells. The very smallest creatures, like bacteria, are a single cell. A grown human is made of about 30 trillion cells, working together in different specialised teams.\n\nMost cells are far too small to see without a microscope. A typical human cell is about a hundredth of a millimetre across. The egg of a bird is unusual: an entire chicken egg is one giant cell, packed with food for the chick that will grow inside it.\n\nDespite huge differences, most cells share a few basic parts. The whole cell is wrapped in a thin flexible cell membrane that decides what gets in and what stays out. Inside is a watery jelly called cytoplasm, in which all kinds of tiny machinery floats. Most cells contain a control centre called the nucleus, which holds the cell's instructions written in a long molecule called DNA. Around the nucleus, smaller structures called organelles do specific jobs: mitochondria release energy from food, ribosomes build new proteins, and so on.\n\nPlant cells have everything animal cells have, plus a stiff outer wall that gives plants their structure, and tiny green chloroplasts that do photosynthesis. That is why a plant can stand up tall without a skeleton.\n\nCells are not a fixed object; they are constantly busy. They grow, take in food, throw out waste, and replace their parts. When a cell has grown enough, it can split into two daughter cells, each with the same instructions. This is how bodies grow from a single starting cell into millions or trillions, and how cuts heal.\n\nNot all of the cells in your body are 'yours'. Living on your skin and especially in your gut are trillions of bacteria, helping you digest food. Together they are called your microbiome.","topics":["life","cells","microscope","membrane","dna"]}
{"id":"seed:en:evolution","source":"seed:en:evolution","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Evolution is the slow change in living things from one generation to the next over very long periods of time. It is how today's huge variety of life — millions of different species — came from much simpler beginnings, billions of years ago.\n\nThe basic engine of evolution is called natural selection. It works like this. No two living things are exactly the same; even kittens from the same litter look slightly different. Some of those differences are passed on from parents to children through a long molecule inside cells called DNA. In any group of plants or animals, some individuals happen to be a little better suited to wherever they live — maybe they run a bit faster, or have a sharper beak, or can stand the cold better. Those individuals tend to survive longer, have more babies, and pass on the helpful traits. Less suited individuals leave fewer offspring. Over many generations, the helpful traits become more common, and the species slowly changes.\n\nGiven enough time, this can produce extraordinary results. The first life on Earth was simple single-celled creatures, more than 3.5 billion years ago. From them came everything else — bacteria, plants, fungi, fish, dinosaurs, birds, mammals, and us. Whales evolved from four-legged land animals that gradually became fully aquatic. Birds evolved from small feathered dinosaurs. The fact that humans share most of our DNA with chimpanzees is because we share a common ancestor a few million years ago.\n\nEvolution does not have a goal. It does not aim at making things 'better' in some general sense. It just keeps the variations that work for the time and place, and lets the rest fade. When the environment changes — say, ice ages come and go, or an asteroid hits — different traits become helpful, and life shifts along.\n\nFossils, comparisons of DNA between species, and direct observation of fast-breeding bacteria adapting to new chemicals all support the same conclusion: living things change.","topics":["life","evolution","natural selection","dna","species"]}
{"id":"seed:en:dinosaurs","source":"seed:en:dinosaurs","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Dinosaurs were a group of land-living reptiles that ruled the Earth for an extraordinarily long time — about 165 million years, from roughly 230 million to 66 million years ago. Compare that to humans, who have been around as a species for less than half a million years.\n\nDinosaurs came in an enormous range of shapes and sizes. Some, like the long-necked Argentinosaurus, were as heavy as a herd of elephants and longer than three buses parked end to end. Others were the size of a chicken. Some walked on four legs, some on two. Some were fierce hunters with rows of dagger-like teeth, and some were peaceful plant-eaters that filed leaves off treetops.\n\nNot every prehistoric animal is a dinosaur. Pterosaurs, the flying reptiles with leathery wings, were not dinosaurs but cousins. Plesiosaurs and ichthyosaurs, the swimming reptiles in the seas, were not dinosaurs either. Mammoths, sabre-toothed cats, and our own ancestors lived much later, after the dinosaur era ended. Strict dinosaurs lived only on land.\n\nWe know about dinosaurs because of fossils — bones, teeth, eggs, and even footprints, slowly turned to stone over millions of years and then dug up by scientists called palaeontologists. From the shape of bones we can work out how an animal moved; from teeth, what it ate; from arrangements of fossils, how groups behaved.\n\nThe age of dinosaurs ended suddenly. About 66 million years ago, a huge asteroid — about 10 kilometres across — slammed into what is now Mexico. The impact threw enormous amounts of dust and rock high into the atmosphere, blocking out sunlight for years. Plants died, then plant-eaters, then meat-eaters. Around three-quarters of all species on Earth went extinct, including every non-bird dinosaur.\n\nBirds are dinosaurs that survived. They evolved from small feathered theropod dinosaurs, and the chicken in your dinner is, very literally, a dinosaur descendant.","topics":["life","dinosaurs","fossils","extinction","palaeontology"]}
{"id":"seed:en:mammals","source":"seed:en:mammals","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Mammals are a group of animals that share a few defining features. They have hair or fur on at least part of their bodies. They are warm-blooded, which means their bodies stay at roughly the same temperature even when the air around them is hot or cold. The young are usually born alive (rather than hatched from eggs laid in the open), and the mother feeds them with milk produced by special glands. That last feature is what gives the group its name — 'mamma' is an old word for breast.\n\nThere are about 6,500 species of living mammals. They include the smallest known mammal, the bumblebee bat, which weighs less than a paperclip; the largest animal that has ever lived, the blue whale, weighing up to 200 tonnes; and everything in between — mice, dogs, dolphins, elephants, kangaroos, monkeys, and humans.\n\nMammals live in nearly every kind of habitat on Earth. Some run on land, some swim full-time in the sea (whales and dolphins), some glide between trees, and some — bats — actually fly with wings made of skin. Underground burrows, deserts, polar ice, and dense jungle all have mammals adapted to them.\n\nMost mammals give birth to live young, but a few are different. Egg-laying mammals, called monotremes, are an old branch of the family that still includes the platypus and the echidna of Australia and New Guinea. Their babies hatch from eggs but still drink milk. Marsupials, including kangaroos, koalas, and possums, give birth to extremely tiny babies that climb up to a pouch on the mother and finish growing there.\n\nThe first mammals appeared more than 200 million years ago, while the dinosaurs still ruled. They were small, mostly nocturnal creatures, the size of mice. After the dinosaurs went extinct, mammals spread into every available habitat and grew into the variety we see today.","topics":["life","mammals","fur","milk","warm-blooded"]}
{"id":"seed:en:birds","source":"seed:en:birds","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Birds are warm-blooded animals with feathers, beaks, and wings. They are the only living creatures with feathers. Almost all birds can fly, though a few — like ostriches, emus, and penguins — have given up flight for running or swimming.\n\nBirds evolved from small feathered dinosaurs more than 150 million years ago. In a real sense, every bird alive today is a dinosaur. Their bones are hollow and light, an adaptation for flight that they share with their ancient ancestors. Their hearts are powerful, and their lungs are exceptionally efficient — they have to be, because flying takes a lot of oxygen.\n\nThere are around 11,000 species of birds, living on every continent including Antarctica. They range in size from the tiny bee hummingbird, smaller than a child's thumb, to the wandering albatross, with wings stretching over three metres tip to tip. Eagles soar high enough to spot a rabbit a kilometre away. Penguins dive deeper than 500 metres into icy water. Hummingbirds hover in place by beating their wings up to 80 times a second.\n\nAll birds lay eggs. The mother (and often the father too) sits on the eggs to keep them warm until the chicks hatch. Some chicks come out helpless, blind, and naked, and rely on their parents to feed them for weeks. Others — like ducklings — are ready to walk and find food within hours.\n\nBirds communicate with sound. Songbirds — robins, blackbirds, sparrows — have specialised voice-boxes that produce intricate songs. Different species have different songs, and many birds even have local 'dialects'. Some birds, including parrots, ravens, and crows, are remarkably clever. Crows can solve puzzles to get food and even use simple tools.\n\nMany birds migrate vast distances each year, flying between summer and winter homes. Some Arctic terns travel from the Arctic to Antarctica and back every year, more than 70,000 kilometres in total — the longest known annual journey on Earth.","topics":["life","birds","feathers","flight","migration"]}
{"id":"seed:en:reptiles-amphibians","source":"seed:en:reptiles-amphibians","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Reptiles and amphibians are two separate groups of animals, but they are often discussed together because they are both cold-blooded — meaning their body temperature follows the temperature of their surroundings. They warm up by basking in the sun and cool down by sitting in shade or water.\n\nReptiles include lizards, snakes, turtles, tortoises, crocodiles, and alligators. Their bodies are covered in dry, scaly skin that holds water in, which is why most reptiles can live happily in dry places. They breathe air with lungs from the moment they hatch, and most lay eggs with tough, leathery shells on land. A few snakes give birth to live young.\n\nReptiles include some impressive specialists. Snakes have no legs and move by sliding on their belly muscles; some can swallow prey larger than their own head by unhinging their jaws. Chameleons can change colour and have eyes that move independently. Crocodiles have hardly changed in 200 million years and have one of the most powerful bites of any living animal. Turtles carry their bony shell as a permanent home.\n\nAmphibians include frogs, toads, salamanders, and a few rare worm-like creatures. Their skin is thin, smooth, and damp, and many actually breathe partly through it. Most amphibians live a kind of double life: they hatch from eggs in water as larvae (a tadpole, in the case of a frog), with gills and a tail for swimming. As they grow, they change body shape — sprouting legs, losing the tail, swapping gills for lungs — and crawl out onto land. The word 'amphibian' comes from a Greek phrase meaning 'two lives'.\n\nAmphibians never got tough scaly skin, so they need to stay near water or damp places. Their permeable skin makes them very sensitive to pollution, which is one reason scientists watch frog populations carefully — falling numbers can be an early warning sign that something is wrong with a habitat.","topics":["life","reptiles","amphibians","frogs","cold-blooded"]}
{"id":"seed:en:insects","source":"seed:en:insects","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Insects are the most successful group of animals on Earth, by a long way. There are more than a million known species of insects — more than every other animal group put together — and probably millions more we have not yet identified. The total number of individual insects alive at any moment is estimated to be around 10 quintillion (10 followed by 18 zeros).\n\nAn insect's body has three main parts: a head with eyes, antennae, and mouthparts; a middle section called the thorax with six legs and (usually) wings attached; and a back section called the abdomen, where most digestion and reproduction happens. Insects have hard external skeletons made of a material called chitin instead of bones inside.\n\nThe six-legs-and-three-body-parts rule is what separates insects from other small creatures. Spiders are not insects: they have eight legs and two body parts. Centipedes and woodlice are not insects either. Bees, ants, butterflies, beetles, dragonflies, mosquitoes, and grasshoppers are.\n\nMany insects go through a startling transformation called complete metamorphosis. A butterfly, for example, hatches from its egg as a hungry caterpillar — a fat worm-like eating machine. When the caterpillar has grown enough, it forms a hard case called a chrysalis around itself. Inside, its body is rebuilt almost from scratch, and a butterfly with completely different anatomy emerges. The same is true of beetles, bees, ants, and flies, each with their own larval stages.\n\nInsects are essential to life as we know it. Bees, butterflies, and many flies pollinate flowering plants, including most of the crops we eat. Ants and termites turn over soil and recycle dead plant matter. Insects are food for huge numbers of birds, frogs, fish, and bats.\n\nA few insects can hurt humans — mosquitoes spread disease, locusts destroy crops — but the great majority are either harmless or helpful. The world without insects would not work.","topics":["life","insects","metamorphosis","pollination","arthropods"]}
{"id":"seed:en:where-babies-come-from","source":"seed:en:where-babies-come-from","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Every living thing on Earth comes from another living thing of the same kind. A new oak tree starts from an acorn that grew on an older oak. A new cat starts from a tiny cell from a mother cat joined with a tiny cell from a father cat. A new human starts the same way: from one cell from the mother joining with one cell from the father.\n\nThe mother's cell is called an egg, and the father's cell is called a sperm. They are far too small to see — much smaller than a grain of sand. When the two join together, the new combined cell carries instructions from both parents. Those instructions are written in a long molecule called DNA, packaged inside the cell.\n\nFrom that single combined cell, an entire new body slowly grows. The cell splits into two, then four, then eight, and so on. Different cells take on different roles: some become heart cells, some become bone cells, some become brain cells, all following the instructions from the parents. In humans, this growing happens inside the mother's body, in a special stretchy organ called the womb. It takes about nine months for a baby to be ready to be born.\n\nAfter the baby is born, the mother's body produces milk to feed it, the same way as in other mammals. Both parents — and often grandparents and other family members — usually help look after the baby until it can walk, talk, and eventually look after itself. Human babies need a lot of care for a long time.\n\nDifferent animals do this in different ways. Birds lay eggs and sit on them until the chicks hatch. Most fish lay thousands of eggs in the water and leave them to develop on their own. Some plants and simple creatures can even make copies of themselves from just one parent. But the basic idea — life producing more life — is the same everywhere.","topics":["life","reproduction","babies","cells","family"]}



